attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit MSB executable, MIPS, MIPS-I version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, no section header

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_yara_results.description: Detects a suspicious ELF binary with UPX compression
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The sample is a MIPS variant of the Mozi P2P botnet. It exhibits multiple malicious behaviors including vulnerability exploitation for propagation (UPnP, HNAP, SOAP), establishing persistence by modifying startup scripts (e.g., `/etc/rc.local`, `/etc/init.d/S95baby.sh`) and remounting filesystems as read-write (`mount -o remount,rw /overlay /`). The malware downloads and executes further payloads, indicated by IOCs such as `http://%s/Mozi.m`, `http://%s/Mozi.a`, and `http://%s/bin.sh`. It also modifies firewall rules using `iptables` to allow its traffic and communicates over a DHT-based P2P network, identified by tags like `[/cnc]` and `[/atk]`.
